That was my idea.

00:00:28.150 --> 00:00:29.100
So...

00:00:30.990 --> 00:00:32.540
Okay.

00:00:32.540 --> 00:00:33.634
We'll wait for...

00:00:33.634 --> 00:00:34.830
What we got?

00:00:34.830 --> 00:00:37.063
We've got quite a few on Instagram.

00:00:38.500 --> 00:00:40.720
Instagram must be just
easier to jump in and out of

00:00:40.720 --> 00:00:42.040
for most people.

00:00:42.040 --> 00:00:44.040
So I'll just give a brief

00:00:44.040 --> 00:00:45.750
on what we're gonna be talking about,

00:00:45.750 --> 00:00:48.980
and then we'll sort of
officially start it.

00:00:48.980 --> 00:00:50.393
Gregory, hey. How you doing?

00:00:52.810 --> 00:00:54.970
So what we're...

00:00:55.810 --> 00:01:00.810
What we keep running into
in comments and questions is

00:01:01.300 --> 00:01:02.450
range of motion.

00:01:02.450 --> 00:01:06.270
Isn't it true that, if you
train one range of motion,

00:01:06.270 --> 00:01:08.920
that you only get stronger
in that one position

00:01:08.920 --> 00:01:10.503
and not in other positions?

00:01:12.905 --> 00:01:15.300
There's a couple different
ways to answer that.

00:01:15.300 --> 00:01:18.870
Clearly that's a violation of
principles of human physiology

00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:21.210
because you don't use
all ranges of motion,

00:01:21.210 --> 00:01:23.360
even when you lift or
when you do anything,

00:01:24.360 --> 00:01:26.610
but that's what we're gonna talk about,

00:01:26.610 --> 00:01:29.180
and then I'll talk about some research

00:01:29.180 --> 00:01:31.350
and then practical applications.

00:01:31.350 --> 00:01:33.850
So what we're gonna be talking about

00:01:33.850 --> 00:01:36.120
has been well documented

00:01:36.120 --> 00:01:39.570
in one particular powerful study,

00:01:39.570 --> 00:01:42.810
which is authored by a guy I worked with

00:01:43.660 --> 00:01:45.960
when I was youth science
officer at Powerplay.

00:01:47.498 --> 00:01:48.810
a guy named Swapan Mukherjee.

00:01:48.810 --> 00:01:53.370
He's the department head
at a university in Ohio.

00:01:53.370 --> 00:01:54.853
Kinesiology department head.

00:01:56.530 --> 00:01:58.640
God, the name of the
university's just escaping me

00:01:58.640 --> 00:02:02.090
at the moment, but, like, smartest guy

00:02:03.020 --> 00:02:05.280
when it comes to exercise physiology.

00:02:05.280 --> 00:02:07.423
Just the best guy to hang out with.

00:02:10.390 --> 00:02:12.200
So I'll be reviewing that

00:02:12.200 --> 00:02:14.687
and then talking about the strength curve.

00:02:14.687 --> 00:02:16.610
You'll probably see
over the top of my head,

00:02:16.610 --> 00:02:17.510
I've got a couple of graphics.

00:02:17.510 --> 00:02:19.239
I realize that wouldn't
show up on the cameras,

00:02:19.239 --> 00:02:22.770
so Chelsea was nice enough
so I could do it on paper

00:02:22.770 --> 00:02:26.563
so you guys could see
much better in the camera.

00:02:27.740 --> 00:02:29.300
All right.

00:02:29.300 --> 00:02:30.880
- [Chelsea] Robert says hello.

00:02:30.880 --> 00:02:32.458
- Robert does?
- Mm-hm.

00:02:32.458 --> 00:02:36.783
Robert. Yeah, hey, Robert, how you doing?

00:02:38.845 --> 00:02:40.450
All right.

00:02:40.450 --> 00:02:42.370
So let's jump into it.

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:43.203
Now...

00:02:44.520 --> 00:02:47.560
When you train a specific range of motion,

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:49.960
is the adaptation only
in that range of motion?

00:02:49.960 --> 00:02:54.370
Okay, just from, like, biology,

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:55.803
you know, high school,

00:02:56.680 --> 00:02:59.950
you know that the length of
a cell, of a muscle cell,

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:02.470
runs the entire length of the muscle,

00:03:02.470 --> 00:03:06.350
and so when a cell is
activated, it's activated.

00:03:06.350 --> 00:03:10.770
It's just a matter of
how short that cell gets.

00:03:10.770 --> 00:03:12.240
There's actin and myosin,

00:03:12.240 --> 00:03:15.730
the two types of filaments
inside these cells,

00:03:15.730 --> 00:03:18.130
and they come together or they don't,

00:03:18.130 --> 00:03:20.370
and the amount of those microfilaments

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:22.590
that come together is the
shortening of the muscle.

00:03:22.590 --> 00:03:25.700
So, you know, when I contract
my bicep, it's short.

00:03:25.700 --> 00:03:27.140
It's long here.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:29.250
So, like, they're shortening,

00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:31.040
but it's not like

00:03:33.678 --> 00:03:35.070
I'm not engaging the muscle

00:03:35.070 --> 00:03:37.843
when it's in its lengthened
position or whatever.

00:03:41.500 --> 00:03:46.500
What we need to look at is
the fact that, functionally,

00:03:47.130 --> 00:03:49.960
I always reference the
term functional fitness

00:03:49.960 --> 00:03:54.520
as one of the most
overused and misused terms,

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:58.290
but we choose to use ranges of motion

00:03:58.290 --> 00:04:00.460
when we have to get a task done

00:04:00.460 --> 00:04:02.910
as opposed to saying I'm
going to lift a static weight

00:04:02.910 --> 00:04:04.660
through a given range of motion.

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:08.430
For example, a sprinter uses
seven degrees of flexion,

00:04:08.430 --> 00:04:09.330
behind their knee.

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:15.270
You have 180 degrees of range
of motion in your inner joint,

00:04:15.330 --> 00:04:17.853
but when you need to run
fast, you only use seven.

00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:19.523
Why?

00:04:20.780 --> 00:04:24.630
It's because that's the range
of motion that is efficient.

00:04:24.630 --> 00:04:29.070
The muscle, the quadricep,
is at its shortest,

00:04:29.070 --> 00:04:33.033
therefore you have access
to the most muscular tissue,

00:04:33.900 --> 00:04:36.830
so you can gauge the cell

00:04:36.830 --> 00:04:40.020
to a higher degree.

00:04:40.020 --> 00:04:41.560
It's not really you're engaging

00:04:41.560 --> 00:04:42.580
one little part of the muscle

00:04:42.580 --> 00:04:44.070
and it's different parts of the muscle

00:04:44.070 --> 00:04:46.290
when the muscle's shorter.

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:48.120
It's the same muscle that's engaging.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:50.650
It's just the degree of engagement

00:04:50.650 --> 00:04:53.653
that happens in that
stronger range of motion.

00:04:55.220 --> 00:04:56.190
So you see sprinters,

00:04:56.190 --> 00:04:58.570
and the idea that a sprinter's
only getting stronger

00:04:58.570 --> 00:05:00.893
in that seven degrees of motion.

00:05:01.750 --> 00:05:03.760
If that were true, then a
sprinter wouldn't be able

00:05:03.760 --> 00:05:06.370
to get out of a chair very well

00:05:06.370 --> 00:05:09.670
because, when their knee is at 90 degrees

00:05:09.670 --> 00:05:10.503
when you're sitting at a chair

00:05:10.503 --> 00:05:11.490
and you get up out of the chair,

00:05:11.490 --> 00:05:13.690
you have no strength, right?

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:16.160
Oh, but they're incredibly
strong in all ranges of motion,

00:05:16.160 --> 00:05:18.520
so it completely translates

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:21.180
as long as the stronger range is fatigued,

00:05:21.180 --> 00:05:25.520
which is why sprinters have
such powerful leg strength,

00:05:25.520 --> 00:05:29.190
and I can't say this about all sprinters,

00:05:29.190 --> 00:05:31.500
but typically, sprinters don't squat

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:33.180
because they don't want
to fire those muscles

00:05:33.180 --> 00:05:34.700
in a different pattern.

00:05:34.700 --> 00:05:35.710
They want to train.

00:05:35.710 --> 00:05:37.720
They do drills, they do
high knees and stuff,

00:05:37.720 --> 00:05:40.210
but that has to do with flexibility.

00:05:40.210 --> 00:05:42.490
That doesn't have to do
with firing the muscle.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:43.890
That's another thing we get.

00:05:45.310 --> 00:05:47.390
They do it with high knees.

00:05:47.390 --> 00:05:48.970
That's not a strengthening event,

00:05:48.970 --> 00:05:53.323
that's a range of motion,
stretching type of activity,

00:05:54.790 --> 00:05:56.180
Based on...

00:05:57.750 --> 00:06:01.230
Well, first, to dispel
that myth completely,

00:06:01.230 --> 00:06:05.410
there's a 1999 study

00:06:05.410 --> 00:06:06.640
by Swapan Mukherjee,

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.950
the guy I mentioned earlier,

00:06:08.950 --> 00:06:12.270
and one of his students, Nick Raverness,

00:06:12.270 --> 00:06:15.037
and Mukherjee and Raverness in 1999

00:06:15.037 --> 00:06:18.450
did a fixed bench press joint angle,

00:06:18.450 --> 00:06:20.320
so they're bench pressing

00:06:20.320 --> 00:06:23.270
just in a very short range of motion.

00:06:23.270 --> 00:06:25.350
What they did is they had people training

00:06:25.350 --> 00:06:27.860
in just this short range of motion,

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:29.740
very short repetitions,

00:06:29.740 --> 00:06:32.530
and they tried to get it
to where they do a failure

00:06:32.530 --> 00:06:34.120
in just this range of motion,

00:06:34.120 --> 00:06:38.000
and then they would go
back to full-range training

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:40.190
to do a post test after
a certain period of time,

00:06:40.190 --> 00:06:41.870
I don't remember how many weeks it was,

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:43.973
of this strong-range-only training.

00:06:46.080 --> 00:06:47.520
What they determined

00:06:48.380 --> 00:06:50.870
was that these individuals
got incredibly strong,

00:06:50.870 --> 00:06:53.543
even in ranges of motion they never used.

00:06:55.110 --> 00:06:56.670
Doesn't that make sense?

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:59.730
Because they were fatiguing
the entire muscle.

00:06:59.730 --> 00:07:02.040
Now, that's not the whole story,

00:07:02.040 --> 00:07:04.242
because what they're really getting

00:07:04.242 --> 00:07:07.450
is a myofibril effect,
so a density of cell

00:07:07.450 --> 00:07:10.870
as opposed to a volume of cell,

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:15.260
so that would be a more strength
versus mass kind of effect,

00:07:15.260 --> 00:07:18.610
even though it's never
quite as one or the other.

00:07:18.610 --> 00:07:21.820
There's a lot of one and a
little of the other sometimes

00:07:21.820 --> 00:07:24.080
and the same vice versa.

00:07:24.080 --> 00:07:26.970
So what's important to point out

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:31.700
is that we have a strength curve,

00:07:31.700 --> 00:07:33.806
so I want you to see the top image,

00:07:33.806 --> 00:07:37.703
and this is what we see, strength curves,

00:07:39.120 --> 00:07:41.340
When... Look at the top image first.

00:07:41.340 --> 00:07:44.660
So when we're in our
weaker range of motion,

00:07:44.660 --> 00:07:48.310
we are capable of a
small amount of weight,

00:07:48.310 --> 00:07:52.203
1/7th what we are in the
stronger range of motion, right?

00:07:53.230 --> 00:07:54.950
But it's not linear.

00:07:54.950 --> 00:07:56.510
There's a steep curve.

00:07:56.510 --> 00:07:58.470
Like, we're real powerful out here,

00:07:58.470 --> 00:08:01.520
and down here, way less powerful,

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:04.873
and then, down here,
way less than even that.

00:08:07.090 --> 00:08:10.800
It's not like we want to

00:08:10.800 --> 00:08:12.280
necessarily

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:15.470
look at it in a linear fashion.

00:08:15.470 --> 00:08:16.860
It's just not.

00:08:16.860 --> 00:08:20.540
And the bone density research
really proves this out here,

00:08:20.540 --> 00:08:23.130
so how do we get

00:08:23.130 --> 00:08:24.900
really heavy loads

00:08:24.900 --> 00:08:27.230
in this range of motion,
and then lighter loads.

00:08:27.230 --> 00:08:31.010
And the reason we want
a variance in the loads

00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:34.180
is to trigger both types
of muscular growth.

00:08:34.180 --> 00:08:38.590
So phase one of fatigue,
when you do an X3 session,

00:08:38.590 --> 00:08:40.470
has to do with that full range.

00:08:40.470 --> 00:08:42.020
Like, I'm firing the whole muscle,

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:44.640
the whole tricep, the whole
pectoral, the whole deltoid,

00:08:44.640 --> 00:08:49.260
and I'm going to fatigue where
everything is most powerful,

00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:51.700
where I'm capable of delivering
the most amount of force.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:54.290
So that shows a structural deficit

00:08:54.290 --> 00:08:55.820
to the central nervous system,

00:08:55.820 --> 00:08:57.850
hence a structural adaptation.

00:08:57.850 --> 00:09:00.770
More myofibril growth, very
aggressive protein synthesis,

00:09:00.770 --> 00:09:03.328
which means the muscles
becomes more dense,

00:09:03.328 --> 00:09:08.290
and that's a very high
power-to-weight ratio muscle.

00:09:08.290 --> 00:09:12.059
Then, as you go to the
phase two type of fatigue,

00:09:12.059 --> 00:09:14.780
when you can't get to
the strong range anymore

00:09:14.780 --> 00:09:16.920
and you're doing a shorter range.

00:09:16.920 --> 00:09:19.010
Like, I'm just going from here to here,

00:09:19.010 --> 00:09:21.660
so let's say I've got 100
pounds here and 300 pounds here,

00:09:21.660 --> 00:09:25.380
so I'm doing a shorter
repetition, let's call it a half,

00:09:25.380 --> 00:09:27.210
but, you know, it's anywhere in there,

00:09:27.210 --> 00:09:29.890
in that sort of middle space,

00:09:29.890 --> 00:09:31.940
so now

00:09:31.940 --> 00:09:33.130
what am I fatiguing?

00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:34.470
It's not the structure of the muscle

00:09:34.470 --> 00:09:35.530
because we already did that,

00:09:35.530 --> 00:09:37.870
which is why I can't get
full extension anymore.

00:09:37.870 --> 00:09:39.990
Now we're running out of ATP, glycogen,

00:09:39.990 --> 00:09:40.840
and creatine phosphate.

00:09:40.840 --> 00:09:42.920
We're running out of the fuels,

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:47.490
and fuel fatigue is a different
type of muscular fatigue.

00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:49.770
Now, when your central nervous system sees

00:09:49.770 --> 00:09:54.770
that you evacuate the fuels
in the cell very quickly.

00:09:54.820 --> 00:09:58.350
It's an irritant. All
exercise is an irritant.

00:09:58.350 --> 00:09:59.650
I really like using that word

00:09:59.650 --> 00:10:00.540
because it...

00:10:02.030 --> 00:10:04.220
It accurately

00:10:04.220 --> 00:10:05.950
tells the story of the fact

00:10:05.950 --> 00:10:09.920
that there's a point to where
certain tissues in the body

00:10:09.920 --> 00:10:11.383
are really shutting down.

00:10:14.850 --> 00:10:16.350
That process,

00:10:16.350 --> 00:10:19.860
the fuel load and storage within the cell,

00:10:19.860 --> 00:10:23.010
becomes irritated
because you're out of it,

00:10:23.010 --> 00:10:25.160
and then you begin to go to fatigue

00:10:25.160 --> 00:10:26.370
in the weaker ranges of motion

00:10:26.370 --> 00:10:27.580
even holding the lighter weight,

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:29.160
which is very easy on the joints,

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:30.500
but it's a deeper level of fatigue,

00:10:30.500 --> 00:10:31.560
so you're getting both

00:10:31.560 --> 00:10:34.890
the absolute maximum myofibril stimulus

00:10:34.890 --> 00:10:36.170
in that phase one,

00:10:36.170 --> 00:10:39.510
and then that phase two
is the diminishing range

00:10:39.510 --> 00:10:41.050
that you're getting.

00:10:41.050 --> 00:10:42.220
I did an infographic.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:45.610
In fact, some of you will
probably post it in the comments.

00:10:45.610 --> 00:10:47.420
An infographic showing
the diminishing range

00:10:47.420 --> 00:10:50.073
of why, why we do that,

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:53.496
and it's super powerful.

00:10:53.496 --> 00:10:56.640
That's also why we do one set

00:10:56.640 --> 00:10:58.330
with slightly higher repetitions.

00:10:58.330 --> 00:11:03.330
That brings me to the second
part of this graphic right here

00:11:04.330 --> 00:11:07.120
which has to do with the strength curve.

00:11:07.120 --> 00:11:08.810
This is the same curve,

00:11:08.810 --> 00:11:11.600
and we didn't draw it
all the way up to 7X,

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:12.820
so just the 5X,

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:14.850
because the reason

00:11:15.770 --> 00:11:19.910
that the latex that people use with X3

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:22.880
is, let's say 5X at extension,

00:11:22.880 --> 00:11:25.270
is because you really want to make sure

00:11:25.270 --> 00:11:26.977
that you're not denying this curve.

00:11:26.977 --> 00:11:30.780
And this is also why we do
higher repetitions with X3,

00:11:30.780 --> 00:11:34.720
because you are so powerful in
the stronger range of motion.

00:11:34.720 --> 00:11:36.670
And just from a bone density perspective,

00:11:36.670 --> 00:11:38.243
those momentary,

00:11:40.010 --> 00:11:43.860
just, engagements that are just isolated,

00:11:43.860 --> 00:11:47.130
like, for example, when I
push with my upper extremities

00:11:47.130 --> 00:11:48.920
to stimulate bone growth,

00:11:48.920 --> 00:11:53.240
at Osteostrong, I can put
4000 pounds through my legs.

00:11:53.240 --> 00:11:54.750
Well, I'm not going to put 4000 pounds

00:11:54.750 --> 00:11:56.320
through my legs with X3

00:11:57.320 --> 00:11:59.560
or any other type of method.

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:03.150
Like, that's why Osteostrong
is so powerful for bone,

00:12:03.150 --> 00:12:05.260
but, from a muscular standpoint,

00:12:05.260 --> 00:12:07.090
I want to fatigue that
stronger range of motion

00:12:07.090 --> 00:12:08.640
with multiple repetitions,

00:12:08.640 --> 00:12:12.630
and I don't want to get
stuck not being able

00:12:12.630 --> 00:12:15.467
to manage my way through these midpoints,

00:12:16.760 --> 00:12:18.730
which are quite a bit
weaker than the strong.

00:12:18.730 --> 00:12:20.820
So first you go to a fatigue in the strong

00:12:20.820 --> 00:12:23.810
because this is linear,
the latex is linear,

00:12:23.810 --> 00:12:27.720
but you're not, but you
do higher repetitions

00:12:27.720 --> 00:12:31.720
and you end up working your way down that,

00:12:31.720 --> 00:12:35.450
that curve with those large repetitions

00:12:35.450 --> 00:12:38.660
because you make sure that
you get to that fatigue there,

00:12:38.660 --> 00:12:40.240
and you're still using a weight

00:12:40.240 --> 00:12:42.690
that's in your capability range

00:12:42.690 --> 00:12:45.080
throughout this whole curve,

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:47.517
so when somebody says,
"Yeah, I got the Elite band

00:12:47.517 --> 00:12:50.030
"and my workout's only like five reps."

00:12:50.030 --> 00:12:53.100
No, it's like, no. Don't do it like that.

00:12:53.100 --> 00:12:55.760
You're not going to get great results.

00:12:55.760 --> 00:12:58.290
You'll get some myofibril probably,

00:12:58.290 --> 00:13:01.210
but you won't get the size
that you're looking for.

00:13:01.210 --> 00:13:02.510
You'll just get the power.

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:08.560
Let's really focus on getting both.

00:13:08.560 --> 00:13:10.433
You want to have both.

00:13:13.130 --> 00:13:14.490
That's really the focus

00:13:15.864 --> 00:13:17.570
of today's Falsehoods of Fitness.

00:13:17.570 --> 00:13:20.207
Yeah, so don't let anybody
tell you, you know,

00:13:20.207 --> 00:13:22.250
"Oh, the range of motion is lighter."

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:25.190
One of my favorite examples is

00:13:26.130 --> 00:13:28.247
somebody says, "Well, you
know, you don't go full range,

00:13:28.247 --> 00:13:30.600
"don't touch the bar to your
chest in the bench press,"

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:32.830
'cause they're competing in
the sport in the bench press,

00:13:32.830 --> 00:13:34.247
and I go, "Yeah, that's great.

00:13:34.247 --> 00:13:35.847
"What about guys who bench with dumbbells?

00:13:35.847 --> 00:13:37.377
"'Cause they can go down even further

00:13:37.377 --> 00:13:39.317
"'cause they don't have
the bar in their way.

00:13:39.317 --> 00:13:41.107
"Are they doing a real bench press?

00:13:41.107 --> 00:13:43.150
"Like, what does real mean?"

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:47.370
So for those who aren't so

00:13:47.370 --> 00:13:49.400
involved in the sport

00:13:50.710 --> 00:13:52.280
of a movement...

00:13:52.280 --> 00:13:53.550
Now, there's nothing wrong with that.

00:13:53.550 --> 00:13:57.220
In fact, there's a lot of extra
users that are using the X3

00:13:57.220 --> 00:13:59.380
as their sort of finishing set

00:13:59.380 --> 00:14:00.970
when they do the regular workout,

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:04.320
so they are still practicing
the sport of their movement.

00:14:04.320 --> 00:14:05.670
'Cause keep in mind,

00:14:05.670 --> 00:14:08.400
whether it's bench presses
or Crossfit movements,

00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:11.130
these are skills as well as power outputs,

00:14:11.130 --> 00:14:13.020
so they gotta keep that skill alive

00:14:13.020 --> 00:14:15.920
and keep in that movement pattern.

00:14:15.920 --> 00:14:18.340
They have to fire those
muscles in that right order.

00:14:18.340 --> 00:14:20.127
So, like, a baseball
pitcher doesn't decide,

00:14:20.127 --> 00:14:21.927
"Oh, I'm just going to bench
press in the off-season.

00:14:21.927 --> 00:14:23.110
"I'm not going to throw a ball."

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:24.250
Mm-mm. No.

00:14:24.250 --> 00:14:26.773
Don't do that 'cause you screw that up.

00:14:29.551 --> 00:14:31.820
The same kind of thing, but

00:14:33.100 --> 00:14:35.090
you don't want to get

00:14:35.090 --> 00:14:37.560
your training stimulus

00:14:37.560 --> 00:14:41.570
confused with what your sport is.

00:14:41.570 --> 00:14:46.500
So you can have a particular
thing that you do,

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:50.210
but you can also train in
a certain way to optimize

00:14:50.210 --> 00:14:52.733
that thing you do and get
more results out of it.

00:14:54.700 --> 00:14:57.030
I think that concludes.

00:14:57.030 --> 00:14:58.530
Time's a little short.

00:14:58.530 --> 00:15:01.083
We've got a bunch of things
we gotta get done today.

